" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 205 "3. \+
 Fundamental Theorem of Algebra.  The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra a
sserts that every non-constant polynomial (with complex-valued coeffic
ients) has a root (a zero, a solution).  A consequence of the " }
{TEXT 320 30 "Fundamental Theorem of Algebra" }{TEXT -1 29 " is that e
very polynomial of " }{TEXT 317 7 "degree " }{TEXT 276 1 "n" }{TEXT 
318 13 " has exactly " }{TEXT 277 1 "n" }{TEXT 319 6 " roots" }{TEXT 
-1 81 ".  An alternate formulation of this consequence would be that e
very non-constant " }{TEXT 314 21 "polynomial of degree " }{TEXT 279 
1 "n" }{TEXT 315 38 " can be factored into a product of a  " }{TEXT 
278 1 "n" }{TEXT 316 16 " linear factors." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 35 "Consider the following polynomials
